What is the perimeter of a rhombus with diagonals of lengths 12 and 16 units? ||| Because the diagonals of a rhombus are perpendicular bisectors of each other, they divide the rhombus into four congruent right triangles.  The legs of one of these triangles measure $12/2=6$ and $16/2=8$ units.  Therefore, the hypotenuse of each triangle measures $\sqrt{6^2+8^2}=10$ units.  Since the side length of the rhombus is equal to the length of the hypotenuse of one of the triangles, the perimeter of the rhombus is $4\cdot 10=\boxed{40}$ units. [asy]
unitsize(3mm);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7pt)+fontsize(8pt));
dotfactor=3;
pair A=(8,0), B=(0,5), C=(-8,0), D=(0,-5), Ep = (0,0);
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw(A--C);
draw(B--D);
label("$6$",midpoint(Ep--B),W);
label("$8$",midpoint(Ep--A),S);[/asy]

A birdbath is designed to overflow so that it will be self-cleaning.  Water flows in at the rate of 20 milliliters per minute and drains at the rate of 18 milliliters per minute.  One of these graphs shows the volume of water in the birdbath during the filling time and continuing into the overflow time.  Which one is it?

[asy]
/* AMC8 2002 #6 Problem */
size(3inch,0.75inch);
for ( int x = 0; x <= 4; ++x )
{

draw((x*1.5,1)--(x*1.5,0)--(x*1.5+1,0));

label(rotate(90)*scale(0.7)*"Volume", (x*1.5-.2,.5));
}
label("$A$", (.5,0), S);
label("$B$", (2,0), S);
label("$C$", (3.5,0), S);
label("$D$", (5,0), S);
label("$E$", (6.5,0), S);
draw((0,0)--(.5,.5)--(1,.5),linewidth(1));
draw((1.5,0.6)--(1.8,0.6)--(2.5,0), linewidth(1));
draw((3,0)--(4,.75), linewidth(1));
draw((4.5,.8)--(5.5,.8), linewidth(1));
draw((6,0)--(6.5,.5)--(7,0), linewidth(1));
[/asy]

