Find the sum of the largest and the smallest of the following: $$4.5 \qquad 4.45 \qquad 0.45 \qquad 0.54$$ ||| We will locate the numbers on the number line.  $4.5$ goes half way between $4$ and $5$ because $0.5=\frac{5}{10}=\frac{1}{2}.$.

Note that $4.45$ goes half way between $4.4$ and $4.5$ because $$0.4=\frac{4}{10}=\frac{8}{20}, \ \ 0.5=\frac{5}{10}=\frac{10}{20}, \ \ \text{and} \ \ 0.45=\frac{9}{20}.$$Likewise, $0.45$ goes half way between $0.4$ and $0.5$ because $$0.4=\frac{4}{10}=\frac{8}{20}, \ \ 0.5=\frac{5}{10}=\frac{10}{20}, \ \ \text{and} \ \ 0.45=\frac{9}{20}.$$Finally, $0.54$ goes just a little bit less than halfway between $0.5$ and $0.6$ because $0.54$ is just a little bit smaller than $0.55,$ which is half way between $0.5$ and $0.6.$

Thus, we can plot all four numbers on the same number line as follows: [asy]
size(8cm); defaultpen(linewidth(0.7));
real eps=0.08; int k; int n=9;
draw((-0.5,0)--(5.5,0),Arrows(4.0));
for(k=0;k<=5;++k)

{

draw((k,-eps)--(k,eps));

label("$"+string(k)+"$",(k,0),2.5*S);

}
for(k=1;k<10;++k)

{

draw((k/10,-eps/2)--(k/10,eps/2));

draw((4+k/10,-eps/2)--(4+k/10,eps/2));

}
dot("4.5",(4.5,0),3*N,red);
dot("4.45",(4.45,0),3*S);
dot("0.45",(0.45,0),3*N,green);
dot("0.54",(0.54,0),3*S);
[/asy] Therefore, the sum of the smallest and the largest numbers is $4.5 + 0.45 = \boxed{4.95}.$

If $\angle ABC$ is a straight angle, give the number of degrees in the measure of $\angle ABD$. [asy] pair A,B,C,D; A = dir(180); D = dir(60); C = dir(0);
draw(B--1.2*A,EndArrow); draw(B--1.2*D,EndArrow); label("A",A,S); dot(A);
label("B",B,S); draw(B--1.2*C,EndArrow); label("C",C,S); label("D",D,dir(135));
label("$6x^{\circ}$",B,NW); label("$3x^{\circ}$",B+.1,NE); dot(D); dot(C);
[/asy] ||| Since \(\angle ABC\) is a straight angle, I think I can set up the equation as \(6x + 3x + 90 = 180\). So, this gives us \(9x + 90 = 180\), which simplifies to \(9x = 90\), and thus \(x = 10\). Therefore, \(\angle ABD = 6x = 6 \times 10 = 60\) degrees, hence the answer is \(\boxed{60}\).

